Question 2

total_CO2<- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(iso3, time) %>% 
  filter(co2 != "NA", name != "NA") %>% 
  summarise(avgCO2 = mean(co2)) %>% 
  filter(iso3 == "USA" | iso3 == "CHN" | iso3 == "IND" | iso3 == "VNM" | iso3 == "KOR")
  
 

total_CO2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, avgCO2, col = factor(iso3))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time (yr)", y = "Average CO2 Emmission (kt)", col = "Countries",
       title = "Average CO2 Emission Over Year")

The graph suggests that out of the 5 countries chosen, China on average emits the highest amount of Co2 after around 2005. China has the greatest positive trend throughout the years with a spike in emissions after year 2000. The US started with the greatest amount of average co2 emission but has not had any major spikes, and is number 2 after 2000. While India, Korea, and Vietnam emits the least amount of Co2 throughout the years in this group.

Question 3

percapita <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(iso3, time) %>% 
  filter(co2_PC != "NA", name != "NA") %>%
  summarise(avgcapita = mean(co2_PC)) %>% 
  filter(iso3 == "USA" | iso3 == "CHN" | iso3 == "IND" | iso3 == "VNM" | iso3 == "KOR")


percapita %>%
  ggplot(aes(time, avgcapita, col = factor(iso3))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time (yr)", y = "Average CO2 Emmission Per Capita (kt)", col = "Countries", 
       title = "Average CO2 Emission CP Over Year")

The graph suggests that the USA has the greatest average Co2 emission per-capita from 1960 to 2019, however there is a steady negative trend with the US releasing less CO2 per-capita in 2019 than compared to previous years. With the other countries, there is a positive trend where they have been increasing CO2 emissions per-capital.

Part 4 - GDP Per Capita:

Question 1

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  select(region, time, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation) %>% 
  filter(time == 1960) %>% 
  filter(GDP_PC != "NA", lifeExpectancy != "NA", name != "NA", totalPopulation != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, color = region, size = totalPopulation)) +
  labs(title = "1960 GDP PerCap. vs Life Expectancy", x = "GDP Per Capita (Constant 2010 US$)", 
       y = "Life Expectancy (Yr)", color ="Continent", size = "Country \n Size")

The scatter plot suggests that as GDP Per Capita increases, so does the life expectancy. Additionally, the plot depicts where continents are on the scale. For instance, we can see that Africa is towards the left end with lower life expectancy and lower GDP CP while Europe is on the right side of the plot with higher life expectancy and higher GDP CP. It also specifies how large a country is by the size of the dot. Larger dot indicates a larger country and smaller dot indicates a smaller country.

Question 2

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  select(region, time, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation) %>% 
  filter(time == 2019) %>% 
  filter(GDP_PC != "NA", lifeExpectancy != "NA", name != "NA", totalPopulation != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, color = region, size = totalPopulation)) +
  labs(title = "2019 GDP PerCap. vs Life Expectancy", x = "GDP Per Capita (Constant 2010 US$)", 
       y = "Life Expectancy (Yr)", color ="Continent", size = "Country \n Size")

The scatter plot suggests that there are many countries with low GDP PC but high Life Expectancy. Also, that some countries from Europe, Asia, Oceania, and Americas have the highest GDP PC and highest life expectancy, although that does not apply to all countries. Many to all of countries in Africa have some of the lowest GDP PC compared to others.

Question 3

Comparing the two plots, from 1960 to 2019, there has definetly been a shift in the gap between GDP CP and life expectancy in countries. More countries have greater life expectancy, and there seem to be less of a gap between countries. For instance, in 1960, Europe was dominatly in the lead, however in 2019, although there is still a gap for some European countries, more countries in Asia and Americas can compare to Europe. Lastly, in 2019 there are more dots in the scatter plot compared to the scatter plot of 1960 indicating that there are more countries being included into the data.

Question 5

gapminder %>%
  select(region, lifeExpectancy, time) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(region)) %>% 
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019) %>% 
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  summarise(avg_exp = mean(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  summarise(prev = lag(avg_exp),
         growth = avg_exp - prev) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(prev), !is.na(growth)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(growth))

Question 6

gapminder %>% 
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region), !is.na (name), !is.na(GDP_PC)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(GDP_PC, fill = factor(time)), position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "GDP Per Capita for years of 1960 & 2019", x = "GDP_PC (Constant US 2010$)",
       y = "Count", fill = "Year")

The histogram above is showing us how many countries had what GDP per capita for the the years of 1960 (red) and 2019 (blue). We can see that a majority of countries had a GDP PC of under 20,000 in both 1960 and 2019, with few having GCP PC over 30,000. Under 5 countries had GDP PC over 30,000 in 1960 but there are around 40 countries with a GDP PC of over 30,000 in 2019.
